<TITLE> SC sets Apr 22 deadline for govt to equip judiciary </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, March 05 (bdnews24.com)  The Supreme Court ordered the government Wednesday to provide judicial magistrates with support staff, vehicles and other needs by April 22. The court asked the government to complete all necessary measures "as soon as possible" and submit detailed reports on or before April 22. A seven-strong full bench of the Appellate Division chaired by chief justice Md Ruhul Amin adjourned proceedings until then. Attorney general Fida M Kamal, submitting gazette documents tied to the matter, told the court: "The government issued the recruitment rules on March 3." The court accepted the documents, but asked when the rest of the activities would be completed. The attorney general said the government was working on the pending matters tied to fully executing the separation of the judiciary. Speaking to bdnews24.com immediately after the proceedings, the attorney general said the government was doing everything in line with the court order. The Supreme Court ordered the government on Dec 12 to provide judicial magistrates with all necessary support staff, vehicles and other requirements in line with an Oct 28 letter of the Ministry of Establishment. The caretaker government officially announced separation of the judiciary from the executive branch on Nov 1, 2007. bdnews24.
